hands_on_practices.solution:
We model the residual distance modulus as  
$$\Delta\mu_{\rm th}(z_i)=A\,z_i,\qquad A\equiv K\Bigl(1-\tfrac34\Omega_{m,0}\Bigr).$$  
The $\chi^2$ for data $(z_i,\Delta\mu_i,\sigma_i)$ is  
$$\chi^2(A)=\sum_{i=1}^3\frac{\bigl(A\,z_i-\Delta\mu_i\bigr)^2}{\sigma_i^2}\,. $$  
Minimizing $\chi^2$ with respect to $A$ gives the normal-equation  
$$0=\frac{\partial\chi^2}{\partial A}
=2\sum_i\frac{z_i\,(A\,z_i-\Delta\mu_i)}{\sigma_i^2}
\;\Rightarrow\;
A_{\rm fit}
=\frac{\sum_i z_i\,\Delta\mu_i/\sigma_i^2}{\sum_i z_i^2/\sigma_i^2}\,. $$  
For our three supernovae:  
- $z_1=z_0,\;\Delta\mu_1=\Delta_0,\;\sigma_1=\sigma_0$,  
- $z_2=2z_0,\;\Delta\mu_2=2\Delta_0,\;\sigma_2=\sigma_0$,  
- $z_3=3z_0,\;\Delta\mu_3=\Delta_0,\;\sigma_3=2\sigma_0$.  

Compute the sums (factor out $z_0\Delta_0/\sigma_0^2$ in numerator and $z_0^2/\sigma_0^2$ in denominator):  
$$\sum_i\frac{z_i\,\Delta\mu_i}{\sigma_i^2}
=\frac{z_0\Delta_0}{\sigma_0^2}\Bigl(1+4+\tfrac34\Bigr)
=\frac{23}{4}\,\frac{z_0\Delta_0}{\sigma_0^2},$$  
$$\sum_i\frac{z_i^2}{\sigma_i^2}
=\frac{z_0^2}{\sigma_0^2}\Bigl(1+4+\tfrac94\Bigr)
=\frac{29}{4}\,\frac{z_0^2}{\sigma_0^2}.$$  
Hence  
$$A_{\rm fit}
=\frac{\frac{23}{4}\frac{z_0\Delta_0}{\sigma_0^2}}
{\frac{29}{4}\frac{z_0^2}{\sigma_0^2}}
=\frac{23\,\Delta_0}{29\,z_0}\,. $$  
Equating to the model $A=K(1-\tfrac34\Omega_{m,0})$ gives  
$$1-\frac34\Omega_{m,0}=\frac{A_{\rm fit}}{K}
=\frac{23\,\Delta_0}{29\,K\,z_0}
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\Omega_{m,0}
=\frac{4}{3}\Bigl(1-\frac{23\,\Delta_0}{29\,K\,z_0}\Bigr)\,. $$
